## Body has transform: scale(--ui-scale) — gotcha for fixed-positioned overlays

`frontend/src/index.css:50-58` applies `transform: scale(var(--ui-scale, 1))`
to `<body>` plus `width/height: calc(100vw / --ui-scale)` to keep visual
size stable across UI-scale settings. This is intentional and avoids a
non-standard `zoom`-property quirk on iPhone SE.

Side effect: any `position: fixed` descendant of `<body>` has `<body>`
as its containing block (CSS Transforms 1: a transformed element wins
over the viewport). Two consequences for floating UI:

1. Fixed-positioned children read their `top/left` in body's pre-transform
   coord space, then get re-scaled. `getBoundingClientRect()` returns
   visual viewport coords (post-transform). Setting
   `top: getBoundingClientRect().bottom + 4` produces an offset that
   grows linearly with distance from body's top-left.

2. `window.innerWidth/innerHeight` are visual viewport dimensions.
   Comparing those against pre-transform top/left for edge detection
   gives wrong answers.

`FloatingMenu` (`frontend/src/app/components/floating/FloatingMenu.tsx`)
solves this by reading `--ui-scale` from `documentElement` and dividing
all viewport-derived inputs (anchor rect, vw/vh, gap, margin) by the
scale before computing position. `menu.offsetHeight` and the `width`
prop stay unscaled — they're already in body coords.

Tried first: portal to `document.documentElement` (= sibling of body,
escapes the transformed containing block). Did NOT work in practice
in this codebase — the menu still rendered as a child of `<body>`
despite `createPortal(jsx, document.documentElement)`. Root cause
unknown; possibly a Vite HMR cache or React-DOM behaviour. Math
compensation is more robust because it doesn't depend on portal
behaviour.

When adding new portalled overlays, EITHER inherit the math from
FloatingMenu OR keep them outside any transformed ancestor.
